<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Halo" class="currentChild" href="Halo">Halo</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
See <a title="Halo Effect" href="Halo_Effect">Halo Effect</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
The term <em>halo</em> also refers to a defect of <a title="Screen Printing" href="Screen_Printing">screen printing</a> characterized by a faint doubling of the printed image, caused by movement of the <a title="Stencil" href="Stencil">stencil</a> under the pressure of the <a title="Squeegee" href="Squeegee">squeegee</a>, typically due to an improperly tensioned screen fabric. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
A <em>halo</em> is also used in screen printing to refer to an enlarged halftone dot, stemming from one of many causes. (Also known as <a title="Fringe" href="Fringe">fringe</a>.) 
</p>
<p id="l7">
In <a title="Halftone" href="Halftone">halftone</a> photography, a <em>halo</em> is a characteristic of a <a title="Soft Dot" href="Soft_Dot">soft dot</a>. See <a title="Soft Dot" href="Soft_Dot">Soft Dot</a>. 
</p>
